name: Santee
description: Welcome to Santee, your local slab and crack training mecca.

boulders.name: Butt Plug
boulders.description: Name speaks for itself

routes.name: Butt Plug Mantle
routes.description: Mantling a butt plug is a one step process

routes.name: East Face L->R
routes.description: Traverse the east face from left to right

routes.name: East Face R->L
routes.description: Traverse the east face from right to left

routes.name: Traverse - left
routes.description: Starting left and below of the ramp on crimps, climb straight up into the ramp, and then back down it to start as for The Ramp

routes.name: The Ramp
routes.description: Starting in the lowest part of the obvious ramp, continue up left as it gets thinner, and then go either straight up or around the corner.

routes.name: Traverse - right
routes.description: Start over to the right of the ramp on what used to be jugs, and now are slightly harder edges. Obviously this can go into any of the other problems

routes.name: Twenty Point Problem
routes.description: Start as with the ramp, but go straight up instead to bad crimps and an obvious diagonal shelf.

routes.name: West Face - right
routes.description: Climb the right side of the west face, starting with a right hand around the arete, and climb up following flake.

routes.name: West Face - left
routes.description: Climb up left side of the west face through the obvious triangular edge and up

boulders.name: Suzie's Boulder
boulders.description: If you're at the dog pile, you'll be looking roughly at the Mean Streak face of the boulder

routes.name: Suzy's Discharge
routes.description: Start low on the obvious crimps, and climb straight up and increasingly less obvious crimps.

routes.name: Suzies face
routes.description: Easiest line up some obvious flakes, somewhere to the right of Mean Streak?

routes.name: Mean Streak
routes.description:
Opposing side pulls to start.
Flaky undercling near the top, so take care.

routes.name: Suzie's Mantle
routes.description: Mantle on the southeast side, next to an adjoining boulder. Jump start to the obvious holds and press it out!

routes.name: Wall Flower
routes.description: Start to the right of Suzie's Discharge and climb up

routes.name: Southeast Face
routes.description: Starting from the right, go up and left, using the obvious under clings.

boulders.name: Round Rock
boulders.description: A predictably oval-like rock seen easily from the trail.

routes.name: Crack Direct
routes.description: See the crack, go to the crack.

routes.name: Face
routes.description: Climb the lightly patina'd face to the right of the crack. Crack is off for maximum fun points.

routes.name: Round Rock Traverse
routes.description: Starting below the crack, or farther left in the crack for more moves, move right toward northeast face and climb up "Thin Face"

routes.name: Crack Traverse
routes.description: Start on the left most part of the crack, checking for lizards first, and follow right and up the crack direct.

routes.name: Ar√©te
routes.description: Up the eat arete

routes.name: Thin Face
routes.description: Northside face

boulders.name: The Dog Pile
boulders.description: The cluster of very large and noticeable boulder, mostly with climbs on the south and east sides

routes.name: Kung Pao
routes.description: Actually a lead climb up the south facing overhanging face.

routes.name: 5.9 Face
routes.description: Left side of the east facing wall, around the corner from Eppersons Lunge.

routes.name: Shockley's Lunge
routes.description: Left of Epperson's Lunge, climb up past black splotches to finish.

routes.name: The 5.8 Face
routes.description: Moving to the right of 5.9 face, a bit easier but a bit higher as well. There is a bolt as needed.

routes.name: Epperson's Lunge
routes.description: A harder lunge right of Shockley's, do the eponymous lunge to an alright hold and mantle.

routes.name: Picket Mantel
routes.description: Follow a gall bladder dish up the rock on the east most section of the pile, in a narrow path between rock and bushes.

routes.name: Seam Slab
routes.description: Keep walking past Picket Mantle till you get to the seam, and then climb it.

routes.name: The Hand Crack
routes.description: Low angle hand crack

routes.name: Mkay
routes.description: Very low angle slab on the boulder ramping up below and to the right of Kung Pao

routes.name: Dog Pile Traverse
routes.description: A right to left traverse, starting at Shockley's Lunge, and finishing up The Hand Crack

boulders.name: Outlander Boulder
boulders.description: Stands alone, totally outside the dog pile area farther to the south at the end of the wash

routes.name: The Outlander
routes.description:
Climb up the weird scoop.
Doesn't get much action so may be dirty.

boulders.name: Bread Loaf Boulder
boulders.description: The squat and unsurprisingly bread loaf shaped boulder just east of the more obvious painted crack boulder.

routes.name: The Bread Loaf
routes.description: Go up the obvious "slice" in the loaf

routes.name: Loaf Right
routes.description: Go up the face to the right of the loaf seam, using obvious underclings and crimps.

boulders.name: Sunset Grill Boulder
boulders.description: You can either scramble your way west from Lightbulb Boulder, or go past No Hands Boulder when turning off from the main trail

routes.name: Thin Crack
routes.description: Jam the obvious thin but nicely angled crack.

routes.name: Face left left
routes.description: Go up the left side of the left face of the boulder, topping out with a mantle.

routes.name: Face left right
routes.description: Go up the right side of the left face of the boulder, topping out with a mantle.

routes.name: East Arete
routes.description: Climb the southeast arete

boulders.name: Painted Crack Boulder
boulders.description: The large boulder with an obvious crack seen from the trail, straight east and a bit than offwidth rock.

routes.name: Painted Traverse
routes.description: Traverse from the left of the crack as far as you'd like, squeezing inside the hewn rock, before finishing up the crack.

routes.name: 10a Face
routes.description: Technical climbing up alright holds on the southwest face of the boulder.

routes.name: The Painted Face
routes.description: Face climb to the right of the crack, past the "sunburst" pattern

routes.name: 10d Face
routes.description: Technical climbing up not so alright holds on the center right part of the southwest face.

routes.name: The Painted Crack
routes.description: Very classic hand jams up the obvious and eponymous painted crack -- a great and not too painful trainer.

boulders.name: Offwidth Rock
boulders.description: The largest boulder viewable from the entrance, with an obvious offwidth crack that beckons you to find its' secrets.

routes.name: Offwidth Problem
routes.description: Climb the offwidth, stopping on the ledge half way to collect yourself before continuing up the easy but definite highball.

boulders.name: No Hands Traverse Boulder
boulders.description: You can either scramble your way west from Lightbulb Boulder, or turn right off the main trail.

routes.name: No Hands Traverse
routes.description: The obvious left to right traverse on the south side of the boulder, scrambling up the face once it feels finished out.

boulders.name: Lightbulb Boulder
boulders.description: The bulb shaped boulder sitting in the middle of the hillside.

routes.name: The Lightbulb
routes.description: On the northwest side of the boulder (from uphill), scramble up, following a sloping crack in the upper section of the bulb.

routes.name: Lightbulb Southwest Sit
routes.description: On the southwest face, sit start the obvious ^ shaped seam that leads into an obvious | shaped seam.

boulders.name: Gumdrop Boulder, The
boulders.description: The east most boulder in Santee, past Painted and Breadloaf.

routes.name: Southeast arete
routes.description: Start on obvious climbs on the southeast arete, moving up and left

boulders.name: EB Boulder
boulders.description: One of the nicest hangout boulders in Santee due to the adjacent eucalyptus tree, it also hosts a few solid lines.

routes.name: The Paint Stripe
routes.description: Climb up the slippery paint streak on the right side of the south face.

routes.name: Right Face
routes.description: Just left of the vertical paint streak, use opposing sidepulls to pull straight up the slab

routes.name: Sit Start Right
routes.description: From the obvious juggy ledge, move up right using obvious crimps.

routes.name: Left Face
routes.description: The stand start version on the left face of the problem, using a variety of holds to go up.

routes.name: Sit Start Left
routes.description: From the obvious juggy ledge, move up left to a not so obvious credit card crimp.

boulders.name: The Donkey Dick
boulders.description: The obviously phallic boulder easily seeable from the entrance to Santee.

routes.name: West Face
routes.description: Also the easiest downclimb, you shimmy up (or down) the gently slabby west side of the boulder.

routes.name: Donkey Dick, Right Arete
routes.description: Staying on the more south facing face, climb up the right arete.

routes.name: East Face - Arete
routes.description: Same as the eponymous Donkey Dick Arete, but stay on the east facing side as long as you can or dare.

routes.name: South Face - Center
routes.description: Straight up the obvious face, either braving the highball or using a bolt to TR.

routes.name: West Face - Arete
routes.description: The south west arete.

routes.name: Traverse
routes.description: Starting on the west face scoop, traverse clockwise all the way around before going straight up.

routes.name: One Cut Above
routes.description:
Starting just right of where Amphitheater's slab ends, grab the left arete and small crimps. Slab up and over.
You should be able to go straight up without using slab as well for similar grade and style.

routes.name: Thin Face
routes.description: Thin crimps to the right of the amphitheater shelf

routes.name: Beneath the Shelf
routes.description: use the big obvious shelf of the ampitheater

routes.name: Face
routes.description: The next slab right from Amp Incline, also avoid the shelf (just used for downclimbing) for full points.

routes.name: Walkman
routes.description: Sidepull and polished foot smear to launch to crimps and then "walk" up

routes.name: Jumpstart
routes.description:
Stand start with a very high foot (or possibly jump it in place) with hands on the arete.
Keep moving up and left, avoiding slab exits.

routes.name: Amp Incline
routes.description: The left most climb on the amphitheater face

routes.name: Eastside Traverse (Left)
routes.description: Starting on right side of the east face, traverse left and then up.

routes.name: Powell Face
routes.description: Either deadpoint to a crimp high off the ground, or utilize some non existent holds to reach it. Finesse your way up.

routes.name: Eastside Traverse (right)
routes.description: Starting on the left side of the east face, traverse right and then up.

routes.name: Amphitheatre Traverse
routes.description: Traverse the eponymous "amphitheater" face, in as many ways and directions as you feel like.

routes.name: Jumpstart Sit
routes.description: SDS to Jumpstart, somehow squeeze your way up to get in the standing position.

boulders.name: Triangle Boulder
boulders.description: An obvious triangle shaped boulder whose overhanging face should be visible to the right as you come up the trail

routes.name: Triangle Boulder, Left Arete
routes.description: Climb the left arete, as tricky and technical as you'd expect.

photos.title: Triangle as seen from the trail

boulders.name: Mudball Cracks
boulders.description: Watch out for critters and bees in these generous cracks, great for learning or honing your techniques.

routes.name: Face
routes.description: The face between left crack and center crack

routes.name: Left Crack
routes.description: The largest of the cracks, but this one has cracks in the cracks

routes.name: Flake Extended
routes.description: A simple extension to Flake, start to the left of the left facing flake, as far as you'd like, and then traverse into the flake and up

routes.name: Mantle
routes.description: Jump up to the obvious triangular feature to the right of the crack, and just mantle it up.

routes.name: Unknown Slab
routes.description: To the right of "Snot a Problem", and with more obvious holds, climb straight up

routes.name: Funky Like a Monkey (aka Lieback Rock Traverse)
routes.description:
Starting on the lieback, traverse left across slab (staying below dyno jug), past the left facing flake, traversing over on crimps, all the way into the finger crack at the far left.
You can also choose to start even farther right around the lieback for more moves and fun.

routes.name: Lieback Rock Lieback
routes.description:
Lieback the obvious right facing rail into some awkward underclings, then following the feature up and right.

You can even choose to lieback facing the wrong way if you'd like.

routes.name: Flake
routes.description: Climb the left facing flake straight up.

routes.name: Crack
routes.description:
Obvious crack on left side of the west facing face.
Beware living creatures nestled within the crack.

routes.name: Lieback Rock Dyno
routes.description: Start on polished holds to dyno up to the obvious shelf jug, or go more slowly if you'd like.

routes.name: Snot a problem
routes.description: To the right of Lieback, climb desperate smears to an even more desperate top out.

routes.name: Sloping Disappointment
routes.description: To the right of the flake, climb the technical face without using the flake or going into the dyno jug.

boulders.name: Bullet Hole Wall
boulders.description:
Named for an actual bullet hole on the north face of this boulder that hugs the Moby Dick on the north side.
Sadly the bullet hole is now a "chiseled out bullet hole", but that doesn't roll off the tongue as well

routes.name: Seam
routes.description: Follow the left angling seam/crack, left of the finger crack.

routes.name: Face left of American Express
routes.description: Climb the obvious and imposing face to the left of American Express. It is high, and it is at least as tricky as AmEx.

routes.name: Friction Seam
routes.description: Starting at the finger crack, but go up right following the seam and smearing your feet.

routes.name: Bullet Hole Wall Crack
routes.description: Follow the slightly right angling finger crack in the middle of the boulder

routes.name: Bullet Hole Face
routes.description: Left of the crack, past the bullet hole. Plenty of variations, including but not limited to ignoring the eponymous hole.

routes.name: Bullet Hole Wall Mantle
routes.description: To the right of Bullet Hole Face, going up and through the diagonal seam. Mantle out the slope, ignoring the blocky jugs up and right.

routes.name: American Express
routes.description: On the west most end of the boulder, very tenuous "credit card" crimps give you just enough to get up this highball.

boulders.name: Beehive Boulder
boulders.description: One of the most versatile and featured boulders in Santee, with cracks, jugs, slopers and crimps

routes.name: Fingercrack
routes.description: Climb the obvious finger crack straight up, or completely avoid it if you want with some supplemental holds.

routes.name: Masochist Crack
routes.description: Ignore the name and enjoy the painless and perfect hand crack

routes.name: Unnamed (Slab)
routes.description: The gentle low angle slab right of the finger crack

routes.name: The Knobs
routes.description: Climb straight up the juggy knobs

routes.name: Iron Cross
routes.description: Starting in Masochist crack, exit straight right to some good holds, feeling like you're in an iron cross before swinging right and topping out on the jugs of The Knobs

routes.name: Off-Width Problem
routes.description: Push yourself between the Beehive boulder and the next and wriggle up.

routes.name: Bear Hug
routes.description: Bear hug the bulge to the left of Masochist Crack.

routes.name: Unnamed Off-Width
routes.description: On the lowest part of the boulder, around the west side, work your way up the off width crack.

routes.name: The Terrible Face
routes.description: Climb the alluring center face of the large boulder right of most of the beehive problems. The top out is high but it's jugs, we swear!

boulders.name: Animal Boulder
boulders.description: A bit hidden behind the bushes, but close to the main trail with a few easy problems.

routes.name: Dead Animal Traverse
routes.description: Right to left traverse of the obvious crack, either following the crack the whole way, or mantle the last overhanging scoop for full Santee experience.

routes.name: West Face Traverse
routes.description: Traverse the west face of the boulder, ending up Long Tall Texan or the Animal Traverse mantle.

routes.name: North Face Traverse
routes.description: Traverse the technical slab on the north face.

routes.name: Ron's Pharmacy
routes.description: A potentially unrepeated ascent up the completely blank NW face of Animal Boulder

routes.name: Long Tall Texan
routes.description: To the left of Animal Traverse crack, find some small holds and go up the bulge. Avoid the crack topout for extra Santee.

boulders.name: Beehive Boulder #2
boulders.description: A bit up the hill from Beehive lies another boulder with a fair amount of crimps and jugs.

routes.name: Unknown Flake
routes.description: The right side of the SW trail facing face, make your way straight up the large hollow flakes

routes.name: Unnamed NW Face
routes.description: SDS on an obvious poor crimp and left hand sidepull (may need a butt pad), go straight up and slightly left up.

routes.name: SW Face Left
routes.description: On the left side of the trail facing SW face, starting on down diagonal edges, work your way up past the stain into flaky undercling.

routes.name: NW Face Right
routes.description: Stand start to the right of the NW face, straight up the face to the left of the arete

routes.name: SW Face Left Corner
routes.description: Starting at obvious edges on the left side of the SW face, climb into and follow the right leaning undercling flake.

boulders.name: The Carousel
boulders.description: So called for its' potential to be traversed all the way around. South Side Undercling should be obvious from the trail.

routes.name: North Side Crimps
routes.description: Ignoring the juggier holds to the left and right, stay on small crimps straight up the north face.

routes.name: East Side SDS
routes.description: Start with obvious underclings and smear feet, working your way up the middle of the face

routes.name: South Side Undercling
routes.description: The obvious undercling, taken for a stand start.

routes.name: North Side SDS
routes.description: A sit start on the down facing triangle, reaching for the obvious chipped hole and up.

routes.name: The Carousel Traverse
routes.description: Traverse the boulder, feel like a pony.

routes.name: Southeast Side Stand
routes.description: Easy stand start on the southeast arete

boulders.name: Undisclosed Boulder
boulders.description: Hard to get to and a bit messy!

boulders.name: Synchronicity Boulder
boulders.description: Obvious boulder at end of the wash, but unfortunately bare of boulder routes.

routes.name: Synchronicity (Aid Crack)
routes.description: Follow the obvious seam up the north side of the boulder.

boulders.name: Moon Boulder, The
boulders.description: Southwest of The Carousel, it's a bit more shrouded from the trail, but should still be easily ID'd by the black spot slab.

routes.name: The Black Spot Problem
routes.description: A Santee slab classic. Look for a small but noticeable black spot, and work your way up to the seam "jug" straight up.

routes.name: Unnamed
routes.description: Climb up the dimple of the southeast face

routes.name: Unnamed
routes.description: On the south face of the boulder, climb up

routes.name: NE face (left)
routes.description: Follow the arete to the left of the black spot, avoiding its' eponymous crimp, and slabbing your way up.

boulders.name: Lonesome Boulder
boulders.description: Up and right from The Carousel, it should be quite noticeable from the main trail.

routes.name: The Flake Right
routes.description: Climb the obvious and large flakes at the northwest corner of the boulder, following the right harder side.

routes.name: Kathleen Turner Overdrive
routes.description:
SDS on small edges, pull up left to good part of the arete and scoot upward.
Not actually on Lonesome Boulder

routes.name: shelf right
routes.description: On the right side of the north face at end of the rock ledge, climb straight up crimps and then mantle out.

routes.name: Uphill face right
routes.description: On the right side of the northeast face, easy and obvious holds

routes.name: Left Shelf Mantle
routes.description: Starting above the shelf jutting out of the ground on the leftmost side of the north face, use the right facing sidepull to pull up to lip and mantle.

routes.name: SW Face
routes.description: Go up obvious edges, but beware a loose flake near the top

routes.name: shelf center
routes.description: To the right of the thin "hueco" in the middle left side of the north face, use the left facing flake to go straight up.

routes.name: The Flake Left
routes.description: Climb the obvious and large flakes at the northwest corner of the boulder, following the left easier side.

routes.name: East corner
routes.description: Use the obvious undercling to pull up and over.

routes.name: Uphill face center
routes.description: Various obvious edges in middle of face alongside narrow northeast boulder face

parking.description: Local park parking lot. From here, a downright criminal would jay walk straight across the road (using cautious use of the median), while law abiding citizens will go east down Mast Blvd to the cross walk and back up
